where the route variable matches the injected variable on the controller exactly.

But, if you are sending the ID directly via a data object, it may be easier to just load the `$request` variable, and then pull the `id`, and subsequently the model with that id, within your method.

Unfortunately, I&#39;m not sure either of these will work as you wish.  I&#39;m not entirely sure what you are trying to do with this create method.  If you are trying to create a new PostPictures model - then what is Laravel supposed to be injecting?  IE if there is no model yet, how can you pull one from the database?  By convention, usually this method doesn&#39;t have an `id` coming in, but you would show a form or something to create a new model here and store it in the `store` method.  As you have it, it looks like a bit of a loop (postpicture -&gt; user -&gt; postpicture).    

Bottom line though is that the error is likely happening because there is nothing sent to that method to allow the model to be injected - no id = no `$postPicture`

