If you want to rotate an object in place, then you&#39;ve to dot the rotation before the translation:

```lang-non
model = translate * rotate;
``` 

If you want to rotate around a point, then you&#39;ve to translate the object (by the rotation radius) and then rotate the translated object:

```lang-none
model = rotate * translate
```

Note, the operations like [`rotate`](https://glm.g-truc.net/0.9.9/api/a00247.html#gaee9e865eaa9776370996da2940873fd4), [`scale`](https://glm.g-truc.net/0.9.9/api/a00247.html#ga05051adbee603fb3c5095d8cf5cc229b) and [`translate`](https://glm.g-truc.net/0.9.9/api/a00247.html#ga1a4ecc4ad82652b8fb14dcb087879284), define a new matrix and multiply the input matrix by the new matrix.  

So In your case the `translate` has to be done after a rotation (`rotate`) around the z axis:

```cpp
vangle+=0.1;

glm::mat4 model1 = glm::mat4(1.0f);

model1 = glm::rotate(model1, glm::radians(vangle), glm::vec3(0, 0, 1)); 
model1 = glm::translate(model1, glm::vec3(50.0f, 0.0f, 0.0f);

model1 = glm::scale(model1, glm::vec3(1, 1, 1));
```

